	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Don't bother contacting Nintendo, you got a form letter. They're extremely picky about who they license, and unless you are actually an established game developer with enough money to show them (as they have capital requirements, if I remember correctly), you have no hope of being licensed. And at this point they no longer support the SNES, so even if you met their licensing requirements they would just tell you that the console isn't supported anymore.
<br />
<br />Echoing what MottZilla said, producing the cartridge is the <strong>last</strong> of your concerns. Worry about that once you have designed, programmed, and tested a game that SNES collectors would actually want to buy.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


